SIMPLE: humbug
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Humbug
<hw>Hum"bug`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. fr.
<ets>hum</ets> to impose on, deceive + <ets>bug</ets> a frightful
object.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An imposition under fair pretenses;
something contrived in order to deceive and mislead; a trick by
cajolery; a hoax.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A spirit of deception; cajolery;
trickishness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who deceives or misleads; a deceitful or
trickish fellow; an impostor.</def> <rj><au>Sir J.
Stephen.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Humbug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Humbug
<hw>Hum"bug`</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Humbugged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Humbugging</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To deceive; to
impose; to cajole; to hoax.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Humbugger</ent>⟦br⟧
